eden","1250–Male":"1250–Overleden","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","ABT 1250":"circa 1250","1227":"1227","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","ABT 1227":"circa 1227","1250":"1250","Cheshire, Eng":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Utkinton, Ches, Eng":"Utkinton, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT 1227–":"about 1227–Deceased","1227–Female":"1227–Deceased","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","ABT 1250":"about 1250","1227":"1227","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","ABT 1227":"about 1227","1250":"1250","Cheshire, Eng":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Utkinton, Ches, Eng":"Utkinton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Swinerton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Swinnerton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Swinnerton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Swynnerton in Staffordshire. The etymology of the placename is uncertain. It may derive from Old English <i>swille</i> ‘sloppy mess, swill’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Alternatively, the first element may be <i>swīn</i> ‘swine, hog’, <i>swān</i> ‘herdsman, peasant’, <i>swan</i> ‘swan’, or <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’."]}]},{"name":"Ellin","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Some consider this the same as Helen, and indeed in Spanish Helen and Ellen are both represented by Elena. A correspondent of Notes and Queries says the name Ellen has no possible connexion with Helen, which is older by a thousand years at least, and that Ellen is the feminine of Alain, Alan, or Allan. It may, however, be the same as Ailean. Ellin, another spelling of Ellen."],"variants":[{"name":"Ailean","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Alan</b> ."]},{"name":"Helen","meanings":["vernacular form of the name (Greek <i>Hēlēnē</i>) borne in classical legend by a famous beauty, wife of Menelaus, whose seizure by the Trojan prince Paris sparked off the Trojan War. Her name is of uncertain origin; it may be connected with a word meaning ‘ray’ or ‘sunbeam’ compare Greek <i>hēlios</i> ‘sun’. It has sometimes been taken as connected with the Greek word meaning ‘Greek’, <i>Hellēn</i>, but this is doubtful. In the early Christian period the name was borne by the mother of the Emperor Constantine, who is now usually known by the Latin version of her name, <i>Helena</i>. She is credited with having found the True Cross in Jerusalem. She was born in about  248 , probably in Bithynia. However, in medieval England it was believed that she had been born in Britain, which greatly increased the popularity of the name there."]},{"name":"Elena","meanings":["form of   Helen  , now used quite frequently in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellin Swinerton was born about 1227, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Sir Thomas Swinerton. She had at least 1 son with Richard Donne."},"et":{"ABT 1227–":"umbes 1227–Surnud","1227–Female":"1227–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","ABT 1250":"umbes 1250","1227":"1227","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","ABT 1227":"umbes 1227","1250":"1250","Cheshire, Eng":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Utkinton, Ches, Eng":"Utkinton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1227–":"noin 1227–Kuollut","1227–Female":"1227–Kuollut","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","ABT 1250":"noin 1250","1227":"1227","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","ABT 1227":"noin 1227","1250":"1250","Cheshire, Eng":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Utkinton, Ches, Eng":"Utkinton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT 1227–":"environ 1227–Décédée","1227–Female":"1227–Décédée","1225–Male":"1225–Décédé","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","ABT 1250":"environ 1250","1227":"1227","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","ABT 1227":"environ 1227","1250":"1250","Cheshire, 